Import data

options(digits = 3)
X1 <- read.table('T1-5.DAT')
head(X1)
##   V1  V2 V3 V4 V5 V6 V7
## 1  8  98  7  2 12  8  2
## 2  7 107  4  3  9  5  3
## 3  7 103  4  3  5  6  3
## 4 10  88  5  2  8 15  4
## 5  6  91  4  2  8 10  3
## 6  8  90  5  2 12 12  4
solar <- X1$V2 # solar radiation column

Construct a Q-Q plot

qqp <- qqnorm(solar)
qqline(solar) # add a reference line

rq <- with(qqp, cor(x, y)) # compute correlation coefficient

We can look up the critical value for test with \(n = 40\) and \(\alpha = .05\) It is \(.9726 > rq=0.969\). Therefore, we reject the hypothesis of normality at level of significance \(\alpha = 0.05\).

4.31

Import and split data

X2 <- read.table('T1-6.DAT')
head(X2)
##   V1  V2  V3  V4  V5 V6
## 1 18 152 1.6 198 0.0  0
## 2 19 138 0.4 181 1.6  0
## 3 20 144 0.0 186 0.8  0
## 4 20 144 3.2 195 0.0  0
## 5 20 149 0.0 218 0.0  0
## 6 21 142 0.8 182 0.8  0
splitX2 <- split(X2[,-6], X2$V6)
nonmult <- splitX2[[1]]
mult <- splitX2[[2]]
nrow(nonmult)
## [1] 69
nrow(mult)
## [1] 29

Construct qqplot and compute rqs

plotqq <- function(col) {
  qqp <- qqnorm(col, main = "");
  qqline(col);
  with(qqp, cor(x, y))
}
layout(matrix(1:10, nrow = 2, byrow = TRUE), respect = TRUE)
par(mar=rep.int(1,4))
nonmult.rqs <-  sapply(nonmult, plotqq)
mult.rqs <-  sapply(mult, plotqq)

nonmult.rqs
##    V1    V2    V3    V4    V5 
## 0.945 0.961 0.956 0.976 0.944
mult.rqs
##    V1    V2    V3    V4    V5 
## 0.971 0.970 0.795 0.979 0.841

As we can see for non-multiple-sclerosis group, only V4 has a qr > 0.97 Thus we remain skeptical about the normality assumption. For multiple-sclerosis group, V1, V3 and V5 all have qrs > 0.97 while qrs of V3 and V5 are less than 0.85.

We can use shaprio test as well to validate the normality assumption.

results_mult <- sapply(mult, shapiro.test)
mult.shaprio_pvalues <- simplify2array(results_mult["p.value", ])
results_nonmult <- sapply(nonmult, shapiro.test)
nonmult.shaprio_pvalues <- simplify2array(results_nonmult["p.value", ])

According to Royston, the normality should be adequate for p-value < 0.1

mult.shaprio_pvalues
##       V1       V2       V3       V4       V5 
## 6.50e-02 7.15e-02 3.96e-07 3.17e-01 3.48e-06
mult.shaprio_pvalues < 0.1
##    V1    V2    V3    V4    V5 
##  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE
nonmult.shaprio_pvalues
##       V1       V2       V3       V4       V5 
## 1.54e-05 4.44e-04 1.19e-04 9.95e-03 1.61e-05
nonmult.shaprio_pvalues < 0.1
##   V1   V2   V3   V4   V5 
## TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE

Therefore, from Shaprio test we conclude that for multiple-sclerosis group the marginal normality for the 4th variable is dubious while that for other variables is convincing, and that for non-multiple-sclerosis group the marginal normality is convincing for all variables.
